SIMPLE: prone
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prone
<hw>Prone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>pronus</ets>,
akin to Gr. <?/, <?/, Skr. <ets>pravana</ets> sloping, inclined, and
also to L. <ets>pro</ets> forward, for. See <er>Pro-</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Bending forward; inclined; not erect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Towards him they bend⟦br⟧
With awful reverence <qex>prone</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Prostrate; flat; esp., lying with the face down; --
opposed to <contr>supine</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which, as the wind,⟦br⟧
Blew where it listed, laying all things <qex>prone</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Headlong; running downward or headlong.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Down thither <xex>prone</xex> in flight.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Sloping, with reference to a line or surface;
declivous; inclined; not level.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Since the floods demand,⟦br⟧
For their descent, a <qex>prone</qex> and sinking land.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackmore.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Inclined; propense; disposed; -- applied to the mind
or affections, usually in an ill sense. Followed by <xex>to</xex>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Prone</xex> to mischief.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Poets are nearly all <qex>prone</qex> to melancholy.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pronely</ent>⟦br⟧
